 nationalists all over Europe, while appealing to the distinctive heritage of Judaism. The proceedings are also important for what they say—and omit—about the Ottoman state that ruled Palestine as well as the Palestinian Arab people living there. This is a foundational primary source in modern Jewish history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 4aArea Studies : Israel Studies. 4aArea Studies : Middle East Studies. 4aHistory : European History. 4aHistory : History. 4aJewish Studies : Jewish Studies. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Israel & Palestine.2bisacsh1 aReimer, Michael J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143847314740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438473147423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438473147/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles